  "A volcanologist collects a lava sample from a Hawaiian eruption that occurred in 1960. She sends it to a lab for Potassium-Argon dating, but the results show an age of 0 years (no measurable Argon-40). Why does this result actually confirm the method works correctly?": "",
  "Hawaiian lava does not contain potassium, particularly regarding this when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "When lava erupts and cools, all argon gas escapes, resetting the radiometric clock to zero; since only about 60 years have passed, virtually no Ar-40 has accumulated yet": "",
  "The lab made an error and should have found a very old age in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The K-Ar method does not work on volcanic rocks, particularly regarding extreme as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "When lava erupts, extreme heat drives off all existing argon gas, resetting the K-Ar clock to zero, and since only decades have passed (geologically insignificant), not enough K-40 has decayed to produce measurable Ar-40, confirming the method's validity.": "",
  "Climate scientists analyzing a 3,000-year-old tree stump compare its ring pattern with a living tree nearby and find an overlapping section of 200 matching rings. They then compare the stump's oldest rings with rings from an even older log found nearby. Why is this overlapping technique valuable?": "",
